Description

Given the boundaries of two intervals. Print the boundaries of their intersection.

Note: Boundaries mean the two ends of an interval which are the starting number and the ending number.

For any interval [l, r], if l > r, print -1.

Input Format

The first line of input contains T, number of test cases.

For each test case, contains only one line - two intervals [l1, r1], [l2, r2].

Output Format

For each test case, if there is an intersection between these 2 intervals, print its boundaries; otherwise, print -1.

Constraints

1 ≤ T ≤ 10^5

1 ≤ l1, l2, r1, r2 ≤ 10^9

Sample Input 1

```
1
1 15 5 27
```

Sample Output 1

```
5 15
```

Sample Input 2

```
1
3 9 5 6
```

Sample Output 2

```
5 6
```

Sample Input 3

```
1
2 5 6 12
```

Sample Output 3

```
-1
```

Note

In Sample Input 1, the intervals are [1,15] and [5,27]. Their intersection is [5,15].

In Sample Input 2, the intervals are [3,9] and [5,6]. Their intersection is [5,6].

In Sample Input 3, the intervals are [2,5] and [6,12]. They do not intersect, so we print -1.



#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
  ios_base::sync_with_stdio(0);
  cin.tie(0);cout.tie(0);

int a,b,c,d;
cin>>a>>b>>c>>d;
if(c<=b && b>=c)
{
   if(d<=b)
   {
      cout<<c<<" "<<d<<endl;
   }
   else
   {
      cout<<c<<" "<<b<<endl;
   }
   
}
else{
   cout<<"-1"<<endl;
}

   
}
